## Opening Scene (Draft)

*The fluorescent lights buzzed overhead, that particular frequency that drilled into Danny's skull after enough hours. He'd been sitting in this plastic chair for seventy-two hours, with only brief breaks to use the bathroom or choke down food he didn't taste. His daughter lay in the hospital bed, her face pale, her body occasionally twitching with phantom distress.*

*The doctors said she was stable. They said she was healing from the infection. They said the psychological trauma would take time to process.*

*They didn't say anything about why Taylor still thrashed in her sleep, muttering about insects. About too many. About everywhere. About crawling.*

*Danny held her handÃ¢â‚¬â€carefully, gently, as if she might shatterÃ¢â‚¬â€and felt completely useless.*

*He'd failed her. He hadn't seen the bullying. Hadn't noticed her isolation. Hadn't protected her from whatever happened at that school. And now she was breaking in front of him and he couldn't help. Couldn't fix it. Couldn't even understand what was hurting her.*

*Annette would have known what to do. She'd sit right here and tell Taylor a story—something beautiful or funny or comforting, something to reach her daughter when nothing else could. But Annette was gone, and Danny had never learned that particular magic. All he could do was hold Taylor's hand and feel utterly, completely useless.*

*A nurse came in to check vitals, and Danny didn't look up. He just sat there, watching his daughter's face twist in distress, and felt something inside him break.*

*LaterÃ¢â‚¬â€he wouldn't remember how much laterÃ¢â‚¬â€he would realize that's when everything changed. When the helplessness became too much. When the need to help, to fix, to protect overwhelmed everything else.*

*When he triggered.*

*But in that moment, Danny Hebert just sat beside his daughter's bed, held her hand, and wished desperately that he could change the story they were living.*

